<PROFILE>_AN-DIQCBAAJFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930917
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: Laporte strong
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Specialist chemicals group Laporte saw its shares jump 35 to 655p after the
company announced a 15 per cent increase in first-half profits to Pounds
51.3m and a raised dividend.
UBS maintained its buy recommendation and its forecast of Pounds 107m for
the full year on the basis that debt was coming down, the proposed
restructuring would cut costs, and there had been a significant boost from
its Evode subsidiary. However, Hoare Govett feels the share price already
reflects any improvement the company has made and, while nudging its
full-year estimate Pounds 3m higher to Pounds 103m, believes the company is
overvalued.
The telecoms sector rebounded after its recent bout of weakness, most of
which was caused by last week's launch of Mercury's One-2-One cellular
service amid worries that the market would be too competitive.
Cellular telephone group Vodafone, particularly badly hit by the offer from
Mercury of free off-peak calls to private subscribers in the London area,
saw some recovery yesterday. Vodafone shares have dropped by 17 per cent in
the last two weeks and yesterday Henderson Crosthwaite was among brokers
deciding that the fall had been overdone.
Analyst Mr Patrick Hickey said the threat from Mercury had been exaggerated.
'The One-2-One launch takes the cellular market into a new stage of
development,' he said. 'Far from losing market share, we believe Vodafone
will benefit from an expanding market.'
He added that the company's overseas expansion plans also left it well
placed in other markets. Vodafone rose 14 to 493p, Cable and Wireless,
owners of Mercury, gained 8 at 828p and BT put on 3 1/2 at 417 1/2 p.
RMC Group, the building materials company, delivered dull results and the
shares slipped 6 to 793p in steady trading. Its profits declined to Pounds
61.6m from last year's Pounds 62.1m and the dividend was held at 6.6p.
Building specialists had forecast between Pounds 62m and Pounds 69m, with
the dividend expected to rise to 7.1p.
Other building materials groups fell in sympathy. Redland lost 12 to 535p,
Spring Ram 2 to 62p, Hepworth 8 to 377p and Heywood Williams 7 to 347p.
In a dull property sector, Moorfield Estates gained 4 at 45p after
announcing a rights issue to help fund a Pounds 13m deal with British Land.
The latter shed 7 to 380p.
Glaxo climbed 12 to 636p on talk of an upgrade by Salomon Brothers. However,
the house said it had raised forecasts earlier when the results were
announced last week.
New Frontiers Development Trust moved ahead 11 to 100p after Credit Lyonnais
Laing placed the 75 per cent stake - some 75m shares - owned by the Merchant
Navy Officers Pension Fund at 94p a share with institutions. The main buyer
was Foreign and Colonial, which took 30m.
A positive annual meeting at Tomkins continued to boost the shares, with a
BZW recommendation also helping the stock add 9 at 237p.
Among transport issues, SG Warburg was said to be positive on British
Airways, which improved 3 to 358p. Figures at the top end of expectations
from Associated British Ports sent the stock 16 ahead to 452p.
British Aerospace was back in favour yesterday after the previous day's
slide of 26p which followed the disappointing interim figures and sharp
profits downgrades.
The change of mood started with Wednesday evening's meeting with
institutions at Hoare Govett, the company's broker. Bargain hunting was also
in evidence and BAe shares bounced 15 to 409p, with volume reaching 2.9m.
TI Group, which retreated on Wednesday in sympathy with BAe, recovered 4 to
344p.
APV shed 1 1/2 to 97p as analysts downgraded full-year expectations after it
reported a 59 per cent fall in interim profits to Pounds 4.9m. NatWest
Securities was among houses that reduced profits expectations, cutting its
forecast for the full year by Pounds 7m to Pounds 15m.
Tyre and exhaust group Kwik-Fit added 4 1/2 at 172 1/2 p on bumper interim
profits.
USM-quoted Bluebird Toys rose 13 to 451p after leaping nearly 90p earlier in
the week. The market was enthused by a promotional deal with MacDonalds, the
hamburger chain, and a sharp rise in profits.
</TEXT>
