<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Increased core demand helps Kwik-Fit to
Pounds 11.5m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HIGHER demand for tyres and exhausts and a third year of stringent cost
control helped Kwik-Fit Holdings report a rise in pre-tax profits to Pounds
11.5m for the six months to August 31 against Pounds 9.74m.
The company had gained a little market share in the period, Mr Tom Farmer,
chairman, said. 'As long as there's cars on the road and as long as the
consumer has money to spend on the repairs to those cars then we will get a
substantial share of that market.'
Kwik-Fit began its push into the brake replacement market in July. 'Early
indications have shown that this could become an important growth area for
Kwik-Fit and by October of this year we will be in a position to offer and
market this service through 90 per cent of our centres,' Mr Farmer said.
The move is expected to cost about Pounds 2.5m in training and advertising
expenses this year. Kwik-Fit believes the brake replacement market is worth
more than Pounds 500m, twice the value of the current exhaust replacement
market.
Group turnover increased 11 per cent to Pounds 132.1m (Pounds 119.2m) on the
back of increased demand for tyres and exhausts. Operating profits rose 36
per cent to Pounds 12.3m (Pounds 9.08m) but the gain at the pre-tax level
was limited by a fall in profits from asset sales to Pounds 207,000 from
Pounds 1.73m.
Capital expenditure fell from Pounds 9m to Pounds 3.3m. Net interest and
other financial charges fell slightly to Pounds 1.06m, compared with Pounds
1.07m.
The board declared an increased interim dividend of 1.5p (1.35p) out of
earnings per share higher at 4.7p, against 3.82p.
COMMENT
Kwik-Fit has done well to gain market share and lift profits in its static
markets and in the face of growing competition from car dealers. There are,
however, challenges to continuing growth. Consumers still prefer lower
margin economy tyres and it will be hard to achieve more than modest growth
in its share of the stable exhaust pipe market it dominates. But the company
and the City have high hopes of its well-timed and inexpensive move into
brakes. But the Netherlands' operations look back on track, making useful
contribution to profits. With pre-tax forecasts about Pounds 21m to Pounds
22m, a multiple of about 20 looks expensive.
</TEXT>
