<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Laporte jumps as Evode result springs
surprise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BOLGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES IN Laporte jumped 6 per cent yesterday after the speciality chemicals
group surprised the City with the speed of its transformation of Evode, the
chemicals and plastic group it bought in January.
Laporte had been accused by some analysts of overpaying when it came in as a
white knight to bid for Evode, which was under siege from Wassall, the
mini-conglomerate. Laporte's agreed offer was Pounds 129m, Pounds 16m more
than Wassall's hostile bid.
Evode made operating profits of Pounds 13.1m in the five months to July 5,
on sales of Pounds 117m, compared with Pounds 14m in the previous year under
its former management.
Mr Ken Minton, Laporte's chief executive, said: 'The integration of the
Evode businesses has been achieved and has enhanced earnings in the first
half, as promised at the time of the acquisition.'
Laporte has moved quickly to trim costs, cutting 189 jobs from Evode's
workforce of 2,305, including a swathe of management.
The head office has been closed, as has a loss-making German subsidiary.
Mr Minton said Evode's profit margins had been lifted from 3.9 per cent to
double figures, and were on course to match the group average of 14 percent.
The Evode acquisition helped Laporte to increase pre-tax profits by 15 per
cent to Pounds 51m on sales which were 37 per cent ahead at Pounds 440m.
Group debt at the half-year was Pounds 170m. This compared with Pounds 190m
immediately after the acquisition of Evode.
The group said this reflected tight control being exercised on all working
capital and capital expenditure.
Negotiations on the sale of parts of Evode identified as non-core were well
advanced.
Group capital expenditure had been sharply reduced from Pounds 29m to Pounds
25.5m.
This included Pounds 2.1m for the Evode companies.
Mr Minton said capital expenditure was now on a downward trend from last
year's total of Pounds 74m and would not exceed Pounds 53m in the full year.
Mr Minton said: 'With the US markets looking more attractive, offset by
subdued European markets, the group expects to sustain progress in the
second half.'
Earnings per share rose by 7 per cent to 20.1p (18.8p). The interim dividend
was lifted by 5.7 per cent to 7.4p (7p).
COMMENT
The sharp increase in the share price reflected what one analyst described
as a 'stupendous' performance from Evode.
There was thus a justifiable smile on the face of Mr Ken Minton, the chief
executive, who had been widely suspected of overpaying for his latest
acquisition. Analysts have upgraded their full-year forecasts to about
Pounds 110m, which puts the shares on a prospective multiple of 15.5. A
group so well placed to benefit from recovery in the UK and US might expect
to be on better than a market average rating at this stage in the cycle, but
there remains suspicion in the City towards the company. which has a large
number of businesses and has caused its share of disappointment in the past.
The performance of its other businesses was also subdued, after stripping
out acquisitions and currency effects. A period of consolidation has been
promised while recent acquisitions are absorbed. Such a pause, combined with
solid trading as demand improves, could see the shares rise in the medium
term.
</TEXT>
