<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / NBC nears Super Channel purchase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROLAND RUDD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NBC, the US television network, is close to clinching the purchase of Super
Channel, the pan-European satellite television channel which claims it is
available in around 50m homes.
The deal is expected to value Super Channel, 64 per cent owned by the
Marcucci family of Italy and 36 per cent per cent by Mr Richard Branson's
Virgin group, at around Dollars 70m.
It is a further sign of the growing competition in the European satellite
television market. BSkyB, parent company of Sky Television, recently
launched a series of new channels, as part of its drive to increase
revenues.
Super Channel is broadcast via the Eutelsat satellite, the rival to Astra,
which carries Sky Television's channels.
NBC, which is owned by the US conglomerate, General Electric, already
broadcasts programmes on Super Channel through its cable channel, CNBC.
Super Channel, which says that the number of its viewers has increased from
8m to 150m over the past five years, resisted a takeover attempt from United
Artists Entertainment, the US cable television and cinema company, in 1990.
But it recently decided that it should be part of a media conglomerate. The
deal with NBC will enable it to pay off its debts, believed to be more than
Pounds 15m.
According to a financier close to General Electric, NBC has been in talks
with Super Channel for some months and hopes to announce completion of the
deal within 10 days.
The Marcucci family, which runs a family business with annual turnover of
Pounds 250m, is expected to use the proceeds from the deal to boost its
other telecommunication interests.
It has television interests in Greece and Italy and has long harboured
ambitions to set up a pan European television production company producing
quality programmes.
Three years ago it bought a series of European satellite and cable
television rights for Super Channel from MGM/UA, the Hollywood studio that
was bought by Mr Giancarlo Parretti's Pathe Communications and is now
controlled by the French bank, Credit Lyonnais.
</TEXT>
