<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Dixons shares leap on plans to sell US chain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Dixons, the UK's largest electrical retailer, leapt 27p to 260p
yesterday as the company announced it was selling its loss-making US chain
Silo to Fretter, another US electrical retailer.
The City welcomed the move as the ideal solution for Dixons to the growing
problems at Silo, which lost Pounds 22.4m in the year to May 1 and cost it
Pounds 36.2m in closure costs. One analyst called it a 'tremendous deal.
Pretty faultless'.
The sale will result in a charge of Pounds 19.8m against Dixons' half-year
profits to cover current-year US trading losses and an exceptional loss on
disposal. A second charge of Pounds 191.1m, relating to goodwill previously
written off to reserves, is a procedure required by new accounting standards
and has no impact on shareholders' funds.
The 185-store Silo chain is being sold to Fretter in return for a 30 per
cent stake in the enlarged Fretter group, Dollars 30m of 5 per cent
convertible preferred stock, and Dollars 15m of 6 per cent preferred stock.
Fretter will change its name to YES] Your Electronics Superstore, given to
three revamped Silo stores in Rochester, New York.
The investment will be accounted for by Dixons as a related company.
The 5 per cent preferred stock could be converted at any time into ordinary
shares, giving Dixons a potential stake of 49 per cent. Dixons said it did
not intend to convert the stock in the short term.
Mr Robert Shrager, finance director, said trading at Silo had continued to
improve in recent months, but it would take some years and further
investment before Silo achieved adequate profits.
Combining Fretter and Silo would create a group better able to compete in
the US market, he added. There was also considerable potential for improving
profits through cutting costs, by streamlining the distribution network and
corporate offices, and closing poorly performing stores.
Dixons future exposure to Silo is limited to the Dollars 50m carrying value
of its investment in Fretter, together with a secured standby credit
facility of Dollars 40m available for 13 months after completion.
Fretter is a Michigan-based electrical retailer operating 101 stores in
three different formats. For the year to January 31, it reported pre-tax
profits of Dollars 8.7m on sales of Dollars 361.1m.
Lex, Page 18
</TEXT>
