<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Jobless rise increases government discomfort: Figures prompt
unease among investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNEMPLOYMENT rose again last month, according to official figures released
yesterday, triggering nervousness on the foreign exchange markets and
unsettling the government further after a week of poor economic statistics.
The jobless total increased a seasonally adjusted 5,800 in August following
a sharply revised increase of 4,300 in July. The number of people out of
work and claiming benefit now stands at 2.92m, or 10.4 per cent of the
workforce.
The August monthly increase was the second in a row and went some way
towards reversing falls in unemployment that occurred between February and
May. However, the jobless total is still lower than it was in April.
The news contributed to unease among investors, already unsettled by an
attack on the prime minister's leadership by Mr Norman Lamont, the former
chancellor. The pound dropped a pfennig to close at DM2.4625.
Yesterday's figures from the department of employment contained other
worrying signals. Average earnings growth remained lodged at 3.5 per cent in
the year to July suggesting that pay settlements have hit bottom ahead of
the rate of inflation.
After the surprise jump in headline inflation earlier this week, the news on
earnings may undermine confidence that inflationary pressures are dead.
There was also a sharp downwards revision to the latest productivity figures
after the rebasing and reweighting of manufacturing output figures. In the
three months to July, output per head grew by 6.7 per cent compared with the
previous three month period. The figure for June was revised down from 8.2
per cent to 7.2 per cent.
Mr Michael Forsyth, employment minister, drew attention to a 20,000 rise in
employment in the three months ending June, the first quarterly rise in
employment for three years. 'A small rise in unemployment of 5,800 is not
unexpected at this stage of the recovery when individual monthly figures
will vary.'
The Treasury said the latest figures indicated a slow labour market recovery
even though they showed small rises in unemployment in the last two months.
Mr John Monks, general secretary of the Trades Union Congress, called for a
1 per cent cut in interest rates and a 'substantial package for growth' in
the November budget.
'These figures show unemployment is still the biggest problem facing the
country. The feeble recovery is now in danger of stalling.' he said.
Optimism declines in labour market, Page 10
</TEXT>
