<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The 88 competitors in the Leeds International Piano Competition have been
whittled down to six; today and tomorrow each will play a concerto with the
City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra conducted by Simon Rattle. BBC2 is
covering the event starting at 6.55 today, continuing until at least 9.30.
Later BBC2 begins another run of KYTV, the comedy about a naff satellite TV
station which, like so many things these days, includes Angus Deayton in a
leading role (10.00). Then, at 11.15, still on BBC2, an event which may
prove to be an inspired idea but which looks pretty odd to me: the first in
a series of compilations from That Was The Week That Was. It is one thing to
watch extracts from TW3 during a day of 1960s nostalgia, but are there
really more than a few vintage TV freaks who want to watch regular re-runs
of programmes 31 years old? We shall see.
Almost everybody seems to have said that the lines in the carefully scripted
programmes of Paul Merton - The Series are not as funny as his unscripted
lines in 'Have I Got News For You' (10.30 C4). They are right.
</TEXT>
