<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Reluctant miners to sell HQ in Durham
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DURHAM miners have reluctantly bowed to history and put their Durham
headquarters - one of the most imposing union premises in the UK - up for
sale.
Red Hill, built in 1915 and financed by Durham Miners Association members'
contributions, is a domed baroque-style grade II-listed building with
landscaped gardens flanked by statues of Durham miners' past leaders.
The complex, which includes a Georgian villa, a gatehouse and houses for
officials of the National Union of Mineworkers, was a powerful symbol of the
time when 180,000 men worked in almost 200 pits in the Durham coal-field.
Today just one pit remains - Wearmouth, which employs just 700 NUM members.
Mr Davy Guy, north-east area president, said the decision to sell Red Hill
was financial, but added: 'It's been made with a heavy heart.'
The NUM would prefer the building to be sold to to a union or educational
organisation, and for ideological reasons is unenthusiastic at the prospect
of Red Hill becoming a corporate headquarters.
But Wilson Kinnair Commercial of Blyth, Northumberland, the agents, believe
office or hotel use might be appropriate. Tender offers are invited by
November 16.
