<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Campaign aims to curb late payments
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Cashflow Commitment, an attempt to shame businesses into paying their
bills on time, is to be launched by Manufacturing Challenge, the self-help
campaign to boost industry based in the north-east.
Companies in the region are to be offered a rubber stamp which will print on
contracts and invoices the words: 'We promise to pay on time - what about
you?'
The uncomfortable slogan is intended to exert pressure so that late payment,
which destroys some companies and cripples others, is reduced.
'Money is like manure - it only works if it's spread around,' said Mr Karl
Watkin, founder of Manufacturing Challenge and chairman of Crabtree, the
Gateshead-based metal-decorating equipment producer. 'If the cash locked up
in unpaid bills was released into the system it could be used by small- and
medium-sized businesses to grow and thrive.'
Late payment of bills was the main issue raised by north-east businesses at
clinics held this summer by Manufacturing Challenge. The 'challenge' is to
double the region's manufacturing base and treble its exports within a
decade.
The Forum of Private Business has estimated that British companies are owed
about Pounds 50bn in overdue debts.
