<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Code of ethics planned for NHS boards
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BOARD MEMBERS of the National Health Service are likely to become subject to
a code of ethics and business behaviour within the next few months, Sir
Duncan Nichol, chief executive, said yesterday.
In June Sir Duncan set up a task force to examine accountability and probity
issues following serious managerial failings in the Wessex and West Midlands
regional health authorities. He told a National Association of Health
Authorities and Trusts conference in London yesterday that the proposed
national ethical code would be one of the likely outcomes.
Another probable result of the task force's work will be a register of
interests for chairmen, board members and directors of health authorities
and trust hospitals. 'Such a register of interest must reassure the public
that the people at the very top of each NHS body have a clear understanding
that private interests and personal gain must play no part in the conduct of
NHS business,' Sir Duncan said.
He added that the NHS was responsible for 15 per cent of public spending and
'mismanagement of these funds, or unacceptable risk taking, is a proper and
understandable cause for public disquiet'.
During the next six months every health authority and trust should begin to
look at its effectiveness as a board, he said. The task force would provide
guidance on good management, including:
Identifying functions that might be carried out by a company secretary
figure.
Establishing a schedule of reserved decisions that could be taken only by
the board.
Producing detailed guidance on functions and accountability of board
sub-committees.
Sir Adrian Cadbury, chairman of the Committee on Financial Aspects of
Corporate Governance which reported last year, told the conference that
boards must provide a proper degree of disclosure of information, and guard
against 'undue concentrations of power'.
</TEXT>
<XX>
