<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Venables hits out at BBC Spurs claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEWART DALBY and PETER BERLIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR TERRY VENABLES, the former chief executive of Tottenham Hotspur Football
Club, last night criticised the BBC over its decision to run a special
edition of its Panorama programme which alleged that he improperly obtained
Pounds 1m to help him buy shares in the club.
The programme also claimed that he and his advisers engaged in a series of
business malpractices including nightclubs, printing and boardgames, and
that there were irregularities in the transfer of England soccer star Paul
Gascoigne from Spurs to the Italian club Lazio.
Mr Venables, who was sacked by Mr Alan Sugar, chairman of Spurs and of the
electronics company Amstrad, is suing for wrongful dismissal.
Last night Mr Venables said: 'It is most regrettable that despite being in
discussion with the producers of Panorama, they failed to inform me of their
decision to broadcast this programme tonight.'
The Panorama investigation claimed that Mr Venables had raised Pounds 1m by
using one of his former companies, Transatlantic Inns. Two months after
resigning as a director he used its assets in a sale and lease-back
operation with another company, Landhurst Leasing.
The assets were the fixtures and fittings of three pubs leased by
Transatlantic Inns. They, together with another public house, which cannot
be traced, raised Pounds 1m. The programme claimed this money was paid to Mr
Venables' company Edennote and some of it then used for the purchase of
shares in Spurs.
The programme also investigated the Gascoigne transfer. Mr Venables has said
he pushed up the transfer price from Pounds 5.5m to Pounds 6.3m with the
help of Mr Gino Santin, a London restaurateur. However, Mr Giancarlo Guerra,
Lazio's finance director, told Panorama that the deal was reached six months
before Mr Santin was involved and the offer was not increased. The fee of
Pounds 200,000 to Mr Santin was paid to a Swiss company.
Late last night Mr Mark Stephens, Mr Venables' solicitor, issued a statement
condemning the Panorama programme as 'wickedly ill-informed' and 'screened
with reckless haste'.
'The programme failed to comply with the BBC's own guidelines to producers
and did not provide Mr Venables with the opportunity to respond to the
partisan and flagrantly untrue allegations,' he said. 'Nor did it broadcast
the statement given by him to the BBC.'
The BBC said: 'Panorama asked Terry Venables to comment but he declined the
programme's normal conditions of interview.'
</TEXT>
