<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Optimism declines in labour market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SLOW and patchy recovery is taking place in the labour market, yesterday's
figures from the Department of Employment showed.
The optimism of the spring, when unemployment fell for four successive
months, has waned following the news of a 5,800 rise in unemployment last
month, and a revised increase of 4,300 in July.
The picture is not as bleak as it was at the end of last year, however. The
jobless total, at 2.9m, is below that of eight months ago and the size of
the workforce in employment had its first quarterly rise for three years in
the second quarter.
The seasonally-adjusted figures reveal that over the past six months
unemployment fell by an average of 7,500 a month compared with a rise of
25,200 a month over the six months to February. The latest three months show
a reversal of the trend, with the total climbing an average 1,800 a month.
Unadjusted, the number of people out of work and claiming benefit rose
30,600 in August to 2.96m. This compares with rises of 71,500 in August last
year and 67,600 in August 1991.
One encouraging aspect of the figures was the news that the workforce in
employment grew by 20,000 to 24.9m in the three months to the end of June.
Employment levels had fallen in every quarter since the end of 1990, even at
the beginning of this year when unemployment was falling.
However, the number employed in manufacturing fell a seasonally-adjusted
11,000 in July compared with June and by 173,000 over the year to July. It
fell 206,000 in the year to July 1992.
The other main highlights of yesterday's figures were:
The rise in the seasonally-adjusted jobless total was confined to women.
Male unemployment fell by 2,000 in August compared with July while female
unemployment rose 7,800.
The number of people joining the count in August was 395,600, compared with
408,000 in the same month a year ago; 369,000 left the count compared with
346,000 last year.
Unemployment rose in all regions other than East Anglia, the south-west and
Scotland.
The stock of vacancies at Jobcentres - about a third of all vacancies in the
economy - increased by 400 in August to their highest level for over two
years. Seasonally-adjusted vacancies have increased on average by 1,500 per
month in the three months to August.
The underlying increase in average weekly earnings in the year to July was
3.5 per cent, the same as the rate in June. Average earnings for
manufacturing rose by 5 per cent in the year to July and for services by
2.75 per cent. Neither changed on the previous month.
Wages and salaries per unit of output - unit wage costs - in manufacturing
were 1.8 per cent lower in the three months to July than in the same three
months a year ago. This compares with a fall of 2.1 per cent in the three
months to June.
Manufacturing output per head rose by 0.1 per cent in the three months to
July compared with the previous three-month period. It was 6.7 per cent
higher than the same period a year ago.
The Department of Employment also released results of the spring Labour
Force Survey, a survey of 60,000 households designed to give a fuller
picture of the labour market.
The survey, which uses the internationally-agreed International Labour
Office definition of unemployment, found that 2.8m people were unemployed
between March and May, a fall of 3.2 per cent since the previous quarterly
survey. On this definition, 13,000 more people were unemployed than the
average monthly number shown by the claimant count.
The survey also said in the three months to May 24.8m people were in
employment, a rise of 0.2 per cent since the previous survey and 5.5 per
cent higher than spring 1984, when it was first produced.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
