<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Campaign to sell education abroad
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Department of Trade and Industry yesterday set up a trade group to
improve the UK's educational exports.
The aim is to improve the marketing of British further and higher education
to foreigners - which already contributes some Pounds 1.5bn annually to the
UK economy - and to make improvements in the markets for providing
government training schemes and scientific equipment.
Baroness Perry, who recently retired as vice-chancellor of South Bank
University, will lead the department's new education and training group. Her
priority will be to improve British competitiveness in bidding for training
contracts in developing countries which are funded by the World Bank and
usually awarded by national governments. She says the UK lags behind Germany
and the US.
The group will aim to re-establish links with Thailand and establish a hold
on other 'emerging markets', such as South Korea and Taiwan.
Baroness Perry claimed that Britain's hold on some of its traditional
markets had been weakened because universities and colleges had competed
against each other. She contrasted this with the closely co-ordinated
marketing effort by independent schools.
</TEXT>
