<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Directors face tough SE rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TOUGH NEW Stock Exchange rules will require directors of listed companies to
set out full details of their remuneration and compensation arrangements if
they are fired.
The new rule removes a loophole which allowed directors simply to make
available a document which contained few details but noted that fuller
information was available elsewhere.
The change is contained in the first revision of the so-called 'Yellow Book'
governing the release of company information since 1984. Its new provisions
come into effect on December 1.
Under the rules, wider access to directors' contracts will be required,
which will have to give details of a director's salary, bonuses and stock
options and performance-related pay. Annual reports will also have to reveal
the unexpired term of any director who is proposed for re-election at the
next annual general meeting.
However, the contracts will only have to be available from the date the
company's next annual general meeting is announced until the date the
meeting is held.
Under the old rules such information about elements of a director's contract
could remain off-limits to a company's shareholders.
Shareholders who succeed in ousting incompetent or profligate management,
only to learn that the severence terms of the director in question require
even more generous sums to be paid to him or her, have been particularly
vexed by the limited disclosure required until now.
The new Yellow Book also raises the thresholds which determine the method
for bringing shares to listing. From December 1 shares worth up to Pounds
25m can be placed entirely with the clients of the sponsor, up from the
previous ceiling of Pounds 15m. Equity shares with a value of more than
Pounds 50m must be marketed to the public, up from the previous ceiling of
Pounds 30m. Between these limits, shares may be marketed partly by a
placing, and partly by an offer for sale or intermediaries offer.
Other new rules are particularly aimed at biotechnology or scientific
research-based companies whose products may take many years to develop. The
exchange wished to set limits on these companies and any company seeking to
have shares traded must have been conducting its activity for at least three
years and be able to produce financial statements for that time.
Also, it must have attracted investment from professionals, be worth at
least Pounds 20m and have the raising of finance to bring identified
products to commercial exploitation as its primary reason for listing.
</TEXT>
