<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Law body urges end to hearsay rule
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Law Commission, the government's law reform advisory body, is calling
for abolition of the rule which prevents witnesses giving evidence
second-hand in civil court, known as the hearsay rule.
The rule has been criticised as confusing and unnecessary. It frequently
results in increased costs and delays by requiring witnesses to attend and
give evidence in person and can result in relevant evidence being excluded
altogether where they cannot attend court.
Judges are critical of the rule because the public finds it difficult to
understand or accept, which undermines confidence in the judicial system.
The rule is also difficult to reconcile with procedural changes introduced
in recent years which were designed to speed up cases and introduce a more
'cards-on-the-table' approach to civil litigation.
Although the commission recommends abolition of the rule it says there is
still a need to make sure litigants are aware of the limitations of using
hearsay rather than direct evidence.
It therefore proposes a number of safeguards, including a duty to give
notice to the other side of the intention to rely on hearsay evidence;
guidelines to help courts in assessing what importance they should attach to
hearsay; and the right for a party to call and cross-examine any witness
whose evidence has been given as hearsay by the opposing side.
The Hearsay Rule in Civil Proceedings, Command 2321. HMSO. Pounds 10.30.
</TEXT>
