<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Schools show wide variation in spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
STATE SCHOOLS in England and Wales show wide variations in the way they
spend their budgets, the Audit Commission said yesterday.
The public spending watchdog said that some schools had five times as many
administrators per pupil as others, while the percentage of school budgets
spent on salaries for teachers varied between 60 per cent and 80 per cent.
Schools in some areas have a much greater ability to raise funds from
voluntary donations and parent-teacher associations. While voluntary funds
raised as much as Pounds 140,000 in a year for some secondary schools,
others managed less than Pounds 20,000.
Mr Andrew Foster, controller of the commission, said that schools should
examine areas where their performance was significantly different from the
average, and take action to improve it if necessary.
Headteachers and governors now oversee total budgets of Pounds 11.6bn
following the government's introduction of local management of schools.
Governing bodies have made widely differing use of their power to set
headteachers' salaries, introduced in 1991.
The commission found that most schools had not increased headteachers' pay
at all during this period. But one primary school had awarded its head 11
points on the 50-point pay-scale (each point is equivalent to roughly Pounds
600), and two had awarded eight points. Total variation is from Pounds
22,404 at the bottom of the scale to Pounds 50,682 when all fifty scale
points have been earned.
Mr David Hart, general secretary of the National Association of Head
Teachers, said the finding vindicated his association's claim that delegated
budgets had left many headteachers without any pay rise at all.
He also described the figures for voluntary funds as disquieting, saying:
'The size of the sums being generated clearly demonstrates that parents are
putting their hands into their pockets to pay for essentials which should be
provided by national and local government.'
He added that he fully supported the commission's work, although he
emphasised that schools could legitimately decide to spend their budget in
different ways.
Grades awarded in GCSE and A-level examinations are fair and accurate,
according to the Independent Appeals Authority for Schools Examinations.
It said yesterday it had heard only nine appeals for exams in summer 1992,
although almost 5m subject entries were made. Mr John Patten, the education
secretary, greeted last year's results by suggesting that standards might
have fallen.
In 1991, 20 appeals were heard with nine allowed.
Adding up the Sums 2: Comparative Information for Schools. HMSO. Pounds 8.
</TEXT>
