<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / De Klerk fails to win over Chief Buthelezi
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE South African government last night failed to persuade Chief Mangosuthu
Buthelezi, leader of the mainly Zulu Inkatha Freedom Party, to return to
constitutional negotiations after a three-month absence.
President F W de Klerk and most of his cabinet held eight hours of talks
yesterday with Chief Buthelezi and senior officials of Inkatha and the
KwaZulu black homeland whose government Chief Buthelezi leads.
Both sides said after the talks that progress had been made, but that no
immediate return to multi-party negotiations was in prospect.
'We made no decision about going back to the talks. It is just not possible
at present,' Chief Buthelezi said at a joint press conference with President
de Klerk, who nonetheless declared 'there is light at the end of the
tunnel'.
The two agreed to set up joint committees to seek further progress.
Inkatha left the talks in protest at a decision to hold multi-racial
elections next April.
Government officials believe it is essential that Chief Buthelezi accept the
constitutional deal which will eventually emerge from these talks. This
could be achieved without his party returning to the multi-party table. The
Inkatha leader has recently returned from Germany and the UK where he came
under heavy pressure to moderate his demand for autonomy in Natal.
Meanwhile an official of the African National Congress said the ANC
president, Mr Nelson Mandela, would ask the United Nations to remove
sanctions against South Africa when he addresses the General Assembly next
week.
Mr Stanley Mabizela said Mr Mandela would call for the repeal of all
remaining sanctions except those against arms sales. Previously, ANC
officials had insisted that the international oil embargo must also remain.
Parliament yesterday began debate on the first of four transition laws that
will give blacks a share of power for the first time.
</TEXT>
