<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / World Trade News: Clinton's fight for NAFTA approval reaches
Chicago
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CHICAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton's fight to gain Congressional approval for the North
American Free Trade Agreement yesterday reached Chicago, where Mr Lloyd
Bentsen, treasury secretary, addressed corporate executives, writes Laurie
Morse in Chicago.
The hundred or so mainly white and male chief executives who listened while
lunching in Continental Bank's private banking atrium were invited because
they were Nafta supporters.
Labour leaders, black politicians, and grassroots environmental organisers
who lead local opposition to the trade pact were absent, as were the ten
members of the Illinois Congressional delegation, all Democrats, who have
indicated opposition to Nafta.
Earlier in the day, the Congressional Black Caucus, which includes Chicago
Democrats, had released a position paper opposing Nafta, saying the minority
business community had never been fully consulted or considered on it.
The Illinois delegation embodies obstacles the Clinton administration must
overcome for Nafta to succeed. Of the state's 20 representatives, only nine
favour the agreement and only two are Democrats - yet Illinois exports to
Mexico have tripled, to Dollars 1.3bn, since 1987.
Mr Bentsen stressed Nafta's economic benefits to US manufactures and told
the luncheon that failure to confirm Nafta would entail political risks for
Mexico.
