<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Clinton consults about healthcare
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
President Bill Clinton (above) yesterday invited 21 of the 700,000 people
who have written to the White House to express their concerns about the
health care system to come to Washington to tell their stories, writes
George Graham.
The tales - of struggling to pay for a relative's care, of being unable to
change a job for fear of losing health insurance, of being charged Dollars
2,407 for a pair of crutches - are fuel to his fire.
Mr Clinton has set about putting his populist campaigning skills to the
service of governing, ahead of what is likely to be the most complex
challenge of his presidency, the reform of US health care.
Yesterday, the president tackled head-on the issue that is likely to become
one of the most controversial elements of his health reform plan  - the
requirement that all businesses must provide health insurance to their
employees, paying at least 80 per cent of the cost.
Mr Clinton said that employers who did not provide health insurance to their
workers were getting a 'free ride' by using a health care system paid for by
those who did. 'It seems to me that it is a fair thing to say everyone in
America should make some contribution to his or her own health insurance,
and all employers should make some contribution,' he added.
