<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / SIB to draw up City 'hit-list': Regulator prepares to ban
'unfit' individuals from investment business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief regulatory watchdog,
is preparing for the first time to ban individuals from the investment
business whose behaviour it believes poses a threat to investors.
In a move likely to alarm some parts of the investment industry, the SIB is
already reviewing several cases and considering bringing charges against
some individuals.
Separately, the Stock Exchange announced measures yesterday requiring
corporate directors to disclose all the terms of their remuneration,
including stock options and bonuses, in a move aimed also at increasing
protection for investors.
For the first time, companies will have to explain how much it will cost
shareholders if the director is dismissed before the contract's expiry date.
Existing rules offer a loophole by which directors can keep some of the most
expensive details private.
Huge payoffs to directors dismissed for incompetence have been a source of
dismay to institutional shareholders, who have been pressing for a greater
say in the terms of executives' contracts for the companies they invest in.
Although unrelated, the moves are aimed at two of the areas that have
attracted the greatest public and political criticism and might help to
deflect assertions that regulators have been lax in protecting investors
since the Financial Services Act was passed in 1986.
The SIB said its intention in banning individuals was 'not intended to
punish'. Instead, its goal will be to protect investors from future damage
and to deter others who might be considering similar activities.
It said: 'We are beginning to draw cases together. We have asked the
recognised bodies to nominate individuals and clearly we could have
individuals under consideration.'
Initially, the SIB intends to use its powers 'sparingly' until it can assess
the costs. 'The disqualification powers will generally be used by SIB to
focus on cases where, in SIB's opinion, there is serious unfitness which is
not being already appropriately addressed,' the SIB said.
Those who are the subject of a ban will have the opportunity to appeal to a
Treasury-appointed tribunal.
The SIB has had the power to ban individuals since its creation, but not
once in its six-year history has it ever considered doing so.
The decision to begin banning individuals stems from a review of the SIB's
authority conducted this year by its chairman, Mr Andrew Large, in which he
considered whether new legislation was needed to protect investors. In
April, Mr Large said he did not believe legislation was necessary but said
the SIB needed to use more fully the powers it did have.
The SIB said: 'In assessing unfitness, SIB will pay attention to an
individual's conduct in relation to SIB's principles and to the risk of
recurrence of misconduct. Evidence about past misconduct and of signs of
persistence, wilfulness, recklessness or negligence, following from that
will be relevant.'
Directors face tough Stock Exchange rules, Page 9
</TEXT>
