<HEADLINE>
FT  17 SEP 93 / Government to revoke export licences to Iraq
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH companies exporting goods to Iraq which are exempt from the United
Nations trade embargo are to have their licences revoked by the government
following the discovery of fraudulent UN and Department of Trade and
Industry documents.
British officials at the UN have confirmed that UK registered companies are
among a number from various countries which have been brought to the
attention of the UN sanctions committee because of the alleged doctoring of
UN documents.
The doctoring involves false statements of export volumes on goods
classified as humanitarian aid, which may have resulted in some companies
breaching UN trade restrictions. UK officials say that they have been left
with no option but to revoke all export licences in order to prevent the
fraud from spreading.
The DTI is understood to be investigating at least one British-based company
after receiving information from US and UK intelligence.
Under the sanctions regime, which was imposed on Iraq after it invaded
Kuwait in August 1990, humanitarian aid includes medicines and baby food.
However, the fraud is believed to involve borderline cases, where the aid
could have a defence-related application, such as vehicle spare parts and
concrete. These cases are subject to UN scrutiny and require a UN letter of
authorisation.
At least 1,200 licences to export humanitarian-related goods have been
granted by the DTI to UK companies since sanctions were imposed. A further
270 supply licences, which allow UK companies to arrange for the supply of
humanitarian-related aid to Iraq through third countries, have been issued.
An estimated 300 of these licence applications have been approved by the UN
sanctions committee. Under existing procedures, a UK company wishing to
supply Iraq with humanitarian aid in borderline cases applies for an export
licence to the DTI, which applies to the UN sanctions committee for a letter
of authorisation. This letter, which details the company, the goods, and the
volumes involved, is sent back to the DTI via the Foreign Office.
According to senior Whitehall officials, goods which have been identified on
the forged documents are not military equipment. Nevertheless, the fraud
related to larger quantities of goods than those permitted under UN
restrictions.
The UK move follows a UN sanctions committee decision in the summer to set
an end of year expiry date on all approved export applications. The
applications previously had no time limit. However, some fraud cases have
involved the same licence being used more than once.
British companies will be told they can apply for new licences. But the
documentation will be on a different paper which officials say is less
susceptible to fraud.
The DTI, sensitive about not undermining UK commercial interests, was
planning to revoke the licencing procedures discretely, contacting companies
before making any kind of public announcement.
The DTI said yesterday it could neither confirm nor deny that it was about
to change its licensing procedures.
</TEXT>
<XX>
