<DATE>930916
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: British Steel busy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Active trading in British Steel saw turnover jump to 24m after UBS, its
broker, said it was a buyer of the stock. The shares bucked the poor market
trend, closing 4 up at 110p, after the securities house, which hosted a
dinner for the company on Tuesday evening, said its move was based on
optimism concerning the progress of discussions with the EC on its plans to
restructure the steel industry.
A trading statement from Allied-Lyons at a meeting of more than 100 brewing
analysts and institutions received a largely cool reception and the shares
dipped in average volume of 3.3m. An analyst said the cautious tone adopted
by Allied contrasted with a more bullish view espoused at its recent agm,
with the resulting decline in the shares.
Allied said the UK brewing market remained tough and that the recovery in
the US was sluggish. Dealers said the fall in the Allied shares, which
closed 18 down at 575p, was limited by yield support.
Mining conglomerate RTZ dropped 20 to 676p as two securities houses reduced
their forecasts for commodity prices and the company's profits.
Goldman Sachs cut its estimate on copper prices to an average of 80 cents a
pound for 1994, against a previous 85. A London spokesman for the US house
said the cut was based on an expected slowdown in world demand for copper.
Goldman estimated that a 10 per cent fall in copper prices could hit RTZ
earnings by Pounds 53m.
Meanwhile, Lehman Bro-thers downgraded its 1993 earnings forecast for RTZ.
Analyst Mr Rob Davies cut his estimate on the group's underlying full-year
earnings to 36.7p a share from 39p, and issued a profits forecast for the
year of 28.5p a share based on the new FRS3 accounting standard.
Stocks with heavy exposure to both London and New York suffered particularly
badly yesterday. Reuters stood out with a fall of 31 to 1549p in spite of a
positive seminar in New York. Shell Transport retreated 11 to 648p and
Rothmans International 'B' shares, already suffering from worries over their
Footsie status, fell 15 1/2 to 646p.
Realisation that the sector had been left behind, coupled with specific
factors, prompted early morning rallies in pharmaceuticals. But the gains
proved unsustainable and most leading pharmaceutical groups barely held
firm.
Glaxo was up 14 at best on US buying but closed a net penny off at 624p. The
US Food and Drug Administration failed to reach agreement on allowing
generic companies to make versions of off-patent inhaler treatments for
asthma. Agreement would have hit Glaxo's Ventolin and helped Medeva, which
has a potential rival to Ventolin. Medeva shed 9 to 106 1/2 p. SmithKline
Beecham 'A' closed flat at 409p after being up 9, and Wellcome retreated
from a high of 730p to 718p, a net fall of 6.
Profit-taking hit the regional electricity companies after a recent good
run, Panmure Gordon arguing that the Recs 'are at both their absolute and
relative all-time highs'. East Midland declined 8 to 529p, as did Yorkshire
to 576p.
Oil group Lasmo returned to profit and its shares rose 5 1/2 to 133 1/2 p.
Mr Simon Flowers of NatWest Securities said Lasmo had set aims six months
ago to cut costs, sell assets and refinance the balance sheet, and those
targets had been 'not just matched but exceeded'.
NatWest Securities was said to have been the big shopper for Tomkins shares,
which hardened 2 to 228p in trade of 5.3m following a positive if exacting
agm at the company.
</TEXT>
