<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / London Stock Exchange: MGN speculation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and CHRISTOPHER PRICE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mirror Group Newspapers strengthened 8 to 186p after announcing a sharp rise
in first-half results to Pounds 69.9m from Pounds 15.3m. The results were
surrounded by speculation that the 54.8 per cent stake held by the group's
administrators - some 220m shares - would be placed yesterday.
Speculation was hotly denied, but several media analysts were being
unusually tight-lipped, leaving the strong impression that they had been
asked to place the shares and had been gagged ahead of the sale. NatWest
Securities, which published a large and bullish piece of research on MGN
only a month ago, was not responding to calls yesterday, and James Capel was
uncommunicative.
Senior traders believed that there was 'no smoke without fire' and that
brokers appointed by the administrator, Arthur Andersen, had been sounding
out possible buyers. Later the market latched on to the argument that the
stake would be placed at 160p a share after an extraordinary meeting of
shareholders on September 23.
