<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / International Company News: Consob may meet Monday to answer
critics
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONSOB, Italy's stock markets and companies watchdog, may meet as early as
next Monday to respond to criticisms of its role and consider a replacement
for one of its five commissioners who is planning to resign.
Last night, the agency issued a statement defending its decision not to
suspend trading in the shares of the troubled Ferruzzi group. Consob has
been attacked for alleged lapses in monitoring Ferruzzi's affairs.
Consob's next meeting is expected to discuss a replacement for Mr Roberto
Artoni, one of its commissioners, whose plan to resign after little more 18
months has been seen as indicative of a deeper malaise in the agency.
The need for a new appointment could give Consob a chance to demonstrate
some independence from Italy's political establishment. Consob's chairmen
have almost invariably been drawn from the Christian Democrat party.
Calls for a full-scale reform of Consob have come from across the political
spectrum, with senior spokesmen from both the opposition Party of the
Democratic Left (the former Communists) and the autonomist Lombard League
demanding changes to make the agency more effective.
This week, the chairman and deputy chairman of the finance committee in the
Chamber of Deputies, the lower house, announced plans to add legislation on
giving Consob greater powers to laws currently being considered on making
share ownership more attractive.
</TEXT>
