<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / International Company News: GM sells Allison division to
specialist buy-out team
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GENERAL MOTORS, the US automotive group, is to sell its Allison Gas Turbine
division to an investor group led by Clayton, Dubilier &amp; Rice, the leveraged
buy-out specialists. Allison makes engines for the aerospace, industrial and
marine markets.
The two sides declined to disclose the value of the deal, but Wall Street
analysts estimated it would be worth around Dollars 300m.
The disposal is the latest in a series by GM designed to concentrate its
energies on improving its lossmaking North American automotive operations.
Other divestments over the past year include its Allison transmission
division, which was sold to ZF Friedrichshafen of Germany.
Clayton, Dubilier &amp; Rice, which manages an equity capital pool of more than
Dollars 1bn, is one of the more prominent US buy-out investors. Its deals
include the Dollars 1.6bn 1991 buy-out of the computer printers group
Lexmark International from International Business Machines.
GM announced in April last year it was putting Allison up for sale. Mr
Joseph Rice, president of Clayton, Dubilier &amp; Rice, said yesterday the firm
had been negotiating with GM for nearly two years. However, he said: 'For
some period of time GM had not really made up its mind that it wanted to
sell this business.'
Clayton, Dubilier &amp; Rice will be investing around Dollars 100m of equity in
the business. Allison's managers are expected to buy between 15 per cent and
20 per cent of company's common stock.
The management investment team will be led by Mr Blake Wallace, general
manager of the division since 1983, who will become president and chief
executive of the independent company, to be called Allison Engine.
Allison, which became a division of GM in 1929, had 1992 sales of around
Dollars 700m. It is profitable, though GM and Clayton, Dubilier &amp; Rice
declined to put a figure on this.
Its most important business is making engines for the aircraft industry. It
has been a supplier for the C-130 military transport since the start of that
programme, and also supplies civilian and military helicopters.
Mr Rice said it had important new products in the pipeline, and saw
particular opportunities in the market for so-called feeder airlines, which
run services into the hubs run by the leading American carriers.
Although the number of leveraged buy-outs has diminished greatly since their
peak in the 1980s, there has been a steady stream of medium-sized deals in
the US over the past two years. Some Wall Street analysts are forecasting a
substantial increase in activity.
</TEXT>
<XX>
