<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / UK Company News: Co-op Bank almost doubles to Pounds 8.1m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOWER bad debt provisions and increased interest income helped to nearly
double pre-tax profits at Co-operative Bank to Pounds 8.1m in the 28 weeks
to July 23.
In interim figures released yesterday, the bank reported earnings of 0.37p
per share, compared with losses of 0.02p in the first half last year.
Mr Terry Thomas, managing director, said: 'We are very pleased. We are ahead
of where we thought we would be.'
The bank reduced provisions against bad debts by 14 per cent to Pounds 19.5m
(Pounds 22.8m). Mr Thomas said the reduction reflected more customers
repaying their debts and a 'cleaning out' of the corporate loan book.
Net interest income was Pounds 69.4m (Pounds 67.9m), after a reduction in
interest receivable to Pounds 133.7m (Pounds 178m) was more than offset by a
reduced interest charge of Pounds 64.3m (Pounds 110.2m).
Dealing profits more than doubled to Pounds 1.8m (Pounds 760,000), while
non-interest income rose substantially to Pounds 55.8m (Pounds 49.2m).
Deposits rose by nearly 9 per cent, which Mr Thomas said partly reflected
the bank's ethical code launched last year. He said 36 per cent of new
customers mentioned this as one reason why they joined.
Staff costs rose to Pounds 43.3m (Pounds 41.3m) including severance payments
and miscellaneous costs of Pounds 3.6m (Pounds 2.2m).
Other expenses jumped to Pounds 43.8m (Pounds 35.9m). These included higher
marketing and promotional costs, enhancing customer services - including a
switch to 24-hour operation of telephone banking and work on centralised
banking administration - technology and other infrastructure developments.
Operating income rose 8 per cent to Pounds 119.4m (Pounds 110.3m). The tax
charge was Pounds 3.1m (Pounds 1.6m). The interim balance sheet showed
contingent liabilities of Pounds 124.4m, down from Pounds 144m.
The bank's figures were presented in the format required by FRS 3, the new
accounting standard on the profit and loss account. Mr Thomas said: 'For Joe
Punter this is just a maze of numbers. And the definitions leave something
to be desired.'
But referring to the greater disclosure of information required by the
standard, he said: 'It must be in the best interests of depositors and
shareholders because it's all hanging out for you to see.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Co-operative Bank.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6021 National Commercial Banks.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
