<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / Nomura lures banking sector team from Smith New Court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDICATIONS of a revival in employment prospects in the London stock market
were emphasised yesterday by confirmation that Nomura's European division
has successfully lured the highly valued banking sector research team away
from Smith New Court.
Mr Michael Lever, former head of the Smith New Court team, is joining Nomura
on terms reported to be worth around Pounds 300,000 a year.
Mr Lever would not discuss his overall package yesterday, commenting that
many elements, including mortgages, and cars can be involved.
Also signing for Nomura yesterday was Mr David Raye, Mr Lever's second in
command at Smith New Court.
Earlier this year, Nomura had similar success in recruiting Smith's oils
team.
Both moves have been seen as evidence of renewed confidence towards its
London operation by Nomura which had previously cut back on its UK
operation.
The Nomura appointments provide further indication of a strong recovery in
recruitment policies in the City of London, at least for provenly able
staff. Mr Lever was rated second in this year's Extel survey of City
analysts, and first by the banks themselves.
He spent nine years with the Bank of England, and thus joins several other
ex-Bank specialists to have joined stock market firms.
Among them are Mr Ian Harnett, chief economist at Strauss Turnbull, UK arm
of Societe Generale, and Mr Albert Edwards, global strategist at Kleinwort
Benson.
There were also reports yesterday of attempts to preserve the stock market
existence of Carr Kitcat &amp; Aitken, the UK stockbroking firm which was
largely closed down last week by its French parent, Banque Indosuez.
</TEXT>
