<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / Lamont delivers attack on Major's leadership: Ex-chancellor
backs rightwing opposition to tax rises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NORMAN LAMONT, the former chancellor, yesterday delivered a wide-ranging
attack on government policy, calculated to weaken Mr John Major's hold on
Downing Street.
Mr Lamont, who was sacked by Mr Major in May, challenged the prime minister
to rule out British participation in European monetary union, endorsed
rightwing opposition to tax increases, and questioned in scarcely coded
language Mr Major's leadership.
He said Britain's ignominious withdrawal from the European exchange rate
mechanism a year ago today had accelerated economic recovery.
But, writing in The Sun, he warned: 'Instead of talking about tax increases,
the government should be looking at spending cuts.' He added: 'Given the
right leadership, the British people could equal the best in the world.'
Mr Lamont's intervention will encourage rightwing Conservative critics of Mr
Major, and could help trigger a leadership challenge this year.
Mrs Teresa Gorman, a consistent critic, said a challenger might emerge in
November unless Mr Major mobilises support at next month's party conference.
Mrs Gorman said Conservative MPs 'must not get bogged down with the idea
that this is an honest man, and therefore impregnable'.
In his Sun article, Mr Lamont warns that, 'unbelievably', plans for monetary
union are being revived by Mr Jacques Delors, president of the European
Commission.
'Fortunately, there is now no ERM for us to rejoin, and there is not likely
to be for some time. What better time for the prime minister to stand up and
say once and for all that Britain should never again have anything to do
with a single currency,' he says.
Mr Lamont urges Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, to bow to rightwing calls
to re-open cabinet talks on next year's public spending and drop his
insistence that tax increases remain an option in the November Budget.
In an article in The Times, also published today, Mr Lamont says he
considered resigning when Britain was forced out of the ERM, but was
dissuaded by Mr Major. 'Had I known he would change his mind as he did, I
would have done so,' he says.
Mr Lamont says the withdrawal was 'a humiliation for the government, the
prime minister and myself'. But he says the government's desire to be 'at
the heart of Europe' was an obstacle to voluntary withdrawal.
</TEXT>
