<HEADLINE>
FT  16 SEP 93 / Factories' unit labour costs head for historic yearly fall
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART and JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PAY bill in manufacturing industry has not grown at all this year and
British manufacturing is heading for a reduction in unit labour costs in
1993 for the first time since 1960, the Confederation of British Industry
said yesterday.
Providing timely backing for the government's freeze on public sector pay
bills next year, announced on Tuesday, the CBI also said that recovery was
not bringing a bounce-back in manufacturing pay settlements and that pay
freezes remained common. Settlements averaged 2.3 per cent in the second
quarter of the year compared with 4 per cent one year earlier.
The CBI said prices and employment prospects were now a downward pressure on
pay. Its latest survey shows that 60 per cent of employees do not expect a
higher pay rise next year.
Mr Howard Davies, CBI director general, said the public sector squeeze for
1994-95 would help reduce private sector expectations. The current year's
1.5 per cent public sector limit had helped take one percentage point off
private sector settlements.
An average reduction of 3 per cent in the first half of this year, combined
with the continuing low level of pay rises, virtually ensures the first
negative figure for the whole year for more than 30 years. The current
position is superior to that in Germany, France, Japan and the US.
Sir Michael Angus, CBI president, said: 'Experience in the US has shown that
it is possible to keep unit labour costs falling even in a recovery phase.'
Economists say it is normal to achieve productivity gains in the first phase
of an upturn as output picks up while the workforce remains static. But the
CBI said that this upturn was not being accompanied by a sharp rise in
hourly labour costs.
There is, however, some evidence that the reduction in pay settlements is
bottoming out. The latest survey to show a slight increase in the last
quarter - from an average increase of 2.09 per cent to 2.49 per cent - comes
from the Engineering Employers Federation.
Employment in manufacturing has been static since December 1992 at 4.2m.
Companies were using more overtime and more part-timers, while the use of
performance-related pay had spread, the CBI said.
</TEXT>
