FT  16 SEP 93 / Observer: Power player
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Probably the only mystery left in crime fiction is why so many of its most
successful practitioners are women.
'It's simple really - women generally don't have direct power over events
and people in their lives. So they kill people in print instead,' says Janet
Cohen, 53, corporate finance director of Charterhouse bank, whose fourth
venture into crime writing, Death among the Dons, has just been shortlisted
for the prestigious Crime Writers' Association Golden Dagger awards.
A qualified solicitor, she writes crime novels under the name Janet Neel.
Her experience of fiction goes way back to 1966, when she spent time
designing 'human player simulations' - war games - for the US defence
department, then busily trying to second-guess the north Vietnamese army.
'I found I could win the games more easily as a guerrilla than a politician
 -just like being in a merchant bank,' she says.
</TEXT>
